  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the procedure of getting admission into IIT for NRIs?",
  "response": "The procedure for Non-Resident Indians (NRIs) to gain admission into the Indian Institutes of Technology (IITs) primarily involves the following steps:\n\n1. **Eligibility Criteria**: NRIs must fulfill the eligibility criteria, which usually includes having completed their 12th grade (or equivalent) with Physics, Chemistry, and Mathematics (PCM) and securing a minimum percentage in these subjects.\n\n2. **JEE Main and JEE Advanced**: NRIs must appear for the Joint Entrance Examination (JEE) Main and, if they qualify, the JEE Advanced. This is the main entrance exam for admission into IITs. However, NRIs also have the option to apply through the Direct Admission of Students Abroad (DASA) scheme, which sometimes allows them to bypass the JEE route.\n\n3. **DASA Scheme**: Under the DASA scheme, NRIs can apply for admission to IITs based on their scores in standardized tests like SAT, ACT, or other equivalent examinations, along with their 12th-grade scores. The DASA scheme is applicable for undergraduate programs.\n\n4. **Application Process**:\n   - **JEE Registration**: If opting for JEE, NRIs need to register for JEE Main and JEE Advanced through the official websites.\n   - **DASA Registration**: For the DASA route, NRIs need to check the official DASA website for application details, important dates, and required documents.\n   \n5. **Documents Required**: Commonly required documents may include:\n   - 12th-grade mark sheet\n   - Passport copy\n   - NRI proof (such as a passport or certificate)\n   - SAT/ACT scores (if applying through DASA)\n   - Other relevant certificates (like birth certificate, etc.)\n\n6. **Counseling and Seat Allocation**: After results are declared, for JEE, candidates will need to participate in the Joint Seat Allocation Authority (JoSAA) counseling process. For DASA applicants, the seat allocation will follow a separate process defined by DASA.\n\n7. **Fee Payment**: Once allocated a seat, candidates will need to pay the requisite fees to confirm their admission.\n\n8. **Visa and Immigration**: After securing admission, NRIs may need to apply for a student visa to study in India.\n\nIt is important for NRIs to regularly check the official websites of IITs and the DASA scheme for the most current information, as policies and procedures can change.",
